<div id="review_4157368194" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4157368194" />
    <a title="Richard Thompson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11657479-richard-thompson"><img alt="Richard Thompson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530711053p2/11657479.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4157368194?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard Thompson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard Thompson" href="/user/show/11657479-richard-thompson">Richard Thompson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11657479-richard-thompson?shelf=russian-lit-history-culture">russian-lit-history-culture</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11657479-richard-thompson?shelf=religion-spiritual">religion-spiritual</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4157368194" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13550457329659912387">I admit it, I found this book by reading JD Salinger&apos;s Franny and Zooey, but I didn&apos;t read it because I wanted to emulate the horrible Glass children or because I wanted to find a new spiritual path through prayer. I read it because I will read any well known Russian book and because I have an outsider&apos;s fascination with the Russian Orthodox Church. From the outside the Orthodox Church seems to have always been the tool of the state and to be bound hand and foot in ritual that is just blah, blah</span>
  <span id="freeText13550457329659912387" style="display:none">I admit it, I found this book by reading JD Salinger's Franny and Zooey, but I didn't read it because I wanted to emulate the horrible Glass children or because I wanted to find a new spiritual path through prayer. I read it because I will read any well known Russian book and because I have an outsider's fascination with the Russian Orthodox Church. From the outside the Orthodox Church seems to have always been the tool of the state and to be bound hand and foot in ritual that is just blah, blah, blah for most of its practitioners. But it is clearly deeply meaningful for millions of people, who are drawn to the particular form of Christianity that the Orthodox Church practices. There is beauty in the ritual - the robes, the icons, the prayers, but there has to be something more than that. This book gave me an inkling of an understanding of a small part of what that something more might be.<br /><br />The form of prayer discussed here is very different from what we conventionally think of as prayer. We all know that we aren't supposed to pray in the words of Janis Joplin "Oh Lord won't you buy me a Mercedes Benz," but we usually think of prayer as either a group recital of a formula prayer or as a heartfelt individual communion with God, seeking relief from troubles, help for others who need it, guidance to understand God's will and a spiritual connection to the deity. Some of that is covered in the type of prayer discussed here, but the main focus of this book is constant repetition of single simple one line Jesus prayer. There is of course deep meaning in the one line, but the practice is more about the repetition of it so it becomes more like a mantra than a conventional prayer. The way that the book tells you to take the prayer into your heart and being is a lot like Buddhist meditation. There is definitely a mystical element here. It's fascinating. I had no idea that this kind of thinking was part of the Orthodox tradition.<br /><br />The other part of the book that was special to me were the many stories about the pilgrim wandering about the Russian countryside and running into people with stories of the hard life of the peasantry and how they found relief through prayer. It's a world that I know well through my reading of Russian history and literature and it is evoked simply and beautifully in this book. If you are a lover of Russian literature and the world of prerevolutionary Russia, this book is worth reading even if you have no interest in the spiritual side of it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13550457329659912387" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

