  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4288479768" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4288479768" />
    <a title="Baylor Heath" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4213209-baylor-heath"><img alt="Baylor Heath" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597354527p2/4213209.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4288479768?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Baylor Heath" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Baylor Heath" href="/user/show/4213209-baylor-heath">Baylor Heath</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4288479768" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3325492822069326303">Ever since I read J.D Salinger&apos;s Franny and Zooey, the story of this pilgrim walking across Russia learning to pray ceaselessly, which is the obsession of that book&apos;s main character, has stayed with me. Well now I&apos;ve read it and I can understand why it occupied Franny&apos;s mind so heavily. This narrativized (supposedly biographical?) manual for ceaseless prayer is transfixing, fascinating, challenging, and honestly, quite arduous. Early on you really wonder how long a story of a guy saying the Jesu</span>
  <span id="freeText3325492822069326303" style="display:none">Ever since I read J.D Salinger's Franny and Zooey, the story of this pilgrim walking across Russia learning to pray ceaselessly, which is the obsession of that book's main character, has stayed with me. Well now I've read it and I can understand why it occupied Franny's mind so heavily. This narrativized (supposedly biographical?) manual for ceaseless prayer is transfixing, fascinating, challenging, and honestly, quite arduous. Early on you really wonder how long a story of a guy saying the Jesus Prayer can go on, and believe me, for awhile! The pilgrim's journey is filled with remarkable stories, lots of instruction, and a deeper dive into Russian Orthodox Christianity than I expected (with a large focus being the pilgrim's learning from the Philokalia, a supposedly key Orthodox text). With my only real exposure to Russian Orthodox tradition in literature being the elements of it in Dostoevsky's The Brothers of Karamazov, its foreignness could be overwhelming, but also strikingly beautiful. I was hesitant to start on the sequel, The Pilgrim Continues His Way, but I'm glad I did. It's narrative is far more simple, with the Pilgrim returning to his mentor's house and sitting around discussing prayer with others there over the table. These characters ask all the questions the average reader like myself has while reading the first volume, like "alright, but how can you really pray all the time? Like, what about when you're working or doing some involved mental activity?" While it can feel like it majors on the minors, you can tell our anonymous author is on to something crucial, something that will stick with me like it did Franny.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3325492822069326303" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

